<br>
He enjoyed the smell of the knotty pines, the song of the birds, and the perpetual shamble of decaying skeletons. Yes, over time he had come to accept the perambulatory habits of his fallen comrades. &quot;Old friendships die hard,&quot; they say in Kaladim. &quot;Old friends die harder still.&quot; It was not unusual for Ryshat to spy an old deceased friend of his shambling through the woods, apparently intent on getting somewhere in a hurry. These rotting, decaying husks of dwarves were always rushing off to somewhere or another, but were always quick with a laugh or to share some &quot;love taps&quot; with an old comrade. Ryshat had spent many happy days in his youth trading blows with his moldering buddies, but now had found that he had outgrown that pastime. <br>
<br>
He now spent his time in the woods, enjoying the uninhibited &quot;naturalness&quot; of it all. Short of actually hugging a tree or foraging for cabbage, some might actually mistake him for a druid. Ryshat shuddered at that thought, of a life of scampering through the woods all nekkid like while picking berries and kissing bears. In Ryshat's mind, the only thing bears were good for were to put his sword in for safe keeping while looking for bigger things to whomp on. <br>
<br>
As Ryshat wandered along, pondering the possible benefits of being able to teleport on top of a giant's head to deliver a killing blow, he heard a voice call out to him. <br>
     &quot;Hello Ryshat.&quot; <br>
<br>
Ryshat stopped in his tracks and looked around. A little further down the trail sat the Great Flower, cross-legged on a stump. <br>
     &quot;Whaaaasssuuuppp!&quot; Ryshat heartily greeted the Great Flower. &quot;What you doin'?&quot; <br>
     &quot;Just sittin on a stump. Waitin' for you, bud.&quot; <br>
     &quot;True. True.&quot; Ryshat replied. <br>
     &quot;It is time to begin your education young Dwarf. If you are to be the leader of the Flower Jihad, there is much you must learn.&quot; the Great Flower told Ryshat. <br>
     &quot;Oh jeez. This is exactly the reason I'm not a magic user. All that book learnin' and nonsense.&quot; Ryshat replied. <br>
<br>
The Great Flower led Ryshat down the trail a little further. Eventually they stopped and the Great Flower went off of the path and started off through the forest. They walked for a while until they came upon a clearing. Ryshat's eyes adjusted as he emerged from the dark forest into the sunny meadow. In the middle of the meadow he saw a grand building, towering into the shy. Elegant wood carvings adorned the building and vines entwined throughout the lattice work to create a building that was imposing as well as warm and inviting. <br>
     &quot;What is this place?&quot; Ryshat queried. <br>
     &quot;It is the Great Guild Hall of the Gods. You have been brought here to learn what it means to be a leader.&quot; the Great Flower said in a very ominous voice. <br>
<br>
The Great Flower led Ryshat up to the guild hall and pushed open the massive doors. Inside Ryshat saw hundreds of tables, with even more hundreds of people eating dinner. There were great heaps of nachos on the tables and kegs of beer and wine flowing from the ceiling. Everyone seemed to be having a grand old time, laughing and carousing. <br>
<br>
Until Ryshat looked more closely. What at first seemed to be general merriment turned out to be frustration and anguish (Ryshat was not know for being very observant). Every person in the Great Guild Hall had a spoon with a ten foot handle to eat with. The diners could easily scoop up food with the spoon, but try as they might they could not bring the ends of the spoons to their mouths. Some tried stretching their arms as far as they could while others tried bracing their arms on the table for leverage. Food spilled, eyes were poked, and tempers were running high. <br>
     &quot;This is terrible. No one is getting what they want and everyone is getting upset and frustrated.&quot; exclaimed Ryshat. <br>
     &quot;What do you think should be done?&quot; the Great Flower queried. <br>
     &quot;I'm not sure. Eat with their hands?&quot; Ryshat answered. <br>
     &quot;Well ... no. That's not quite the answer I was looking for.&quot; <br>
     &quot;Uh.. oh! I know! They should grip the spoons closer to the head. Make the spoons closer to their mouths!&quot; Ryshat said very excitedly, as if he had figured out the answer to a great riddle. <br>
     &quot;Hmmmm. Well, no. I'm sorry. That won't work.&quot; <br>
     &quot;Yes it would. Here, let me show you.&quot; Ryshat said as he headed to a table and started to pick up a spoon. <br>
     &quot;No, no, no. Not like that. I'm trying to teach you something here.&quot; <br>
     &quot;Well, ok. But I still think holding the spoon...&quot; <br>
     &quot;Stop it! That's not what I'm talking about. Follow me.&quot; At which point the Great Flower led Ryshat into another room of the Great Dining Hall. <br>
<br>
In this room Ryshat saw more people eating. Each one of them had ten foot spoons, but something was different this time. Everyone was using their ten foot spoon to feed each other. Everyone was paired off and getting food on their spoon to feed to the person across from them. The Great Flower looked down at Ryshat and beamed a smile. <br>
     &quot;See Ryshat. This is what I wanted to teach you.&quot; <br>
     &quot;What, how to spread germs? Ewww. I won't let anyone drink out of my flask much less eat off my silverware.&quot; Ryshat said with a disgusted look on his face. <br>
The Great Flower continued with great exasperation, &quot;No... look at them Ryshat. They are using teamwork. Everyone gets what they need because everyone works together.&quot; <br>
     &quot;Hmmm. Good point. I see what you mean. Working alone may work occasionally, but to truly get a fulfilling experience, you need to be able to depend on others.&quot; <br>
     &quot;Exactly.&quot; The Great Flower said with great satisfaction. <br>
<br>
Ryshat and the Great Flower looked at each other. A feeling of understanding passed between them. The Great Flower felt confident in his abilities to teach this rather thick dwarf how to be a great leader. <br>
     &quot;Hey, can we go in the other room now and I can show you what I was saying about choking up the grip on the spoon?&quot; <br>
The Great Flower rolled his eyes and said, &quot;I think a better idea is to get out of here before you start a food fight.&quot; <br>
     &quot;A food fi...? GREAT IDEA! Hang on.&quot; Ryshat exclaimed as he headed for the biggest pile of drippy, gooey nachos he could see. <br>
<br>
The Great Flower grabbed Ryshat by the scruff of the neck before he could do any damage and dragged him out of the guild hall. <br>
     &quot;Jeez. And I thought you were supposed to be a fun God.&quot; Ryshat said with the demeanor of a petulant child. <br>
     &quot;I think I've had enou ... er ... you've learned enough today young dwarf. I'll let today's lesson sink in and we shall learn more at a later time.&quot; <br>
<br>
With this the Great Flower spread wide his petals and disappeared into the heavens in a blinding flash of light. <br>
<br>
As Ryshat sat there in the clearing, pondering what he had been taught, he heard a cackle off in the distance. <br>
     &quot;I'd know that laugh anywhere. That must be Stumpwater Jack! He must have died ... oh ... at least three years ago. I should go over and beat the crap out of him for old times sake.&quot; <br>
<br>
And at that, Ryshat headed off into the woods, secure in the knowledge he would be a great leader of men. Or at least a great hitter of things.<br>
